<F P=100> Brazil </F>
<H3> <TI>   Relations With Cambodia Normalized </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PY2903032594 Sao Paulo GAZETA MERCANTIL in Portuguese 28 Mar 
94 p 3 </F>

<F P=103> PY2903032594 </F>
<F P=104>  Sao Paulo GAZETA MERCANTIL </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Portuguese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Article by Maria Helena Tachinardi] </F>
  [Text] Brasilia -- On 25 March, Brazil and Cambodia 
normalized relations when representatives from the two countries 
met at United Nations headquarters in New York and signed a 
joint communique. 
  Brazil first established diplomatic relations with the 
Kingdom of Cambodia in 1961, establishing representation in 
Phnom Penh concurrent with the Brazilian Embassy in New Delhi, 
India. Afterward that representation became concurrent with the 
Brazilian Embassy in Bangkok. According to the Brazilian 
Foreign Ministry, the representation in Phnom Penh was closed 
down in 1966, but not because relations had been broken between 
the two countries. Following the internal pacification of 
Cambodia under the leadership of Prince Norodom Sihanouk, which 
was endorsed by Brazilian diplomacy, the Brazilian Government 
suggested the normalization of bilateral relations, which was 
confirmed on 25 March with the joint communique. Brazil will 
open an embassy in Phnom Penh concurrent with the embassy in 
Bangkok. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

