<F P=100> Peru </F>
<H3> <TI>   Government To Help Mexico Fight Terrorism </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PY2803203694 Madrid EFE in Spanish 1531 GMT 27 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> PY2803203694 </F>
<F P=104>  Madrid EFE </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Lima, 27 Mar (EFE) -- The Peruvian media reported 
today that the Mexican Government has asked Peru to help their 
anti-terrorist struggle. 
  The Lima daily EXPRESO reports that within the next few days 
two National Police Counterterrorism Directorate (Dincote) 
experts will travel to the Mexican capital with President 
Alberto Fujimori's authorization. 
  EXPRESO cites high-ranking police sources who state that the 
officers are Colonel Juan Gonzalez Sandoval and Lieutenant 
Colonel Alberto Sarmiento Gutierrez. 
  It adds that Gonzalez and Sarmiento will be in Mexico for at 
least 10 days. 
  Mexican officials want to learn Peruvian methods in facing a 
possible upsurge of terrorism following the Chiapas rebellion 
and the death of presidential candidate Luis Donaldo Colosio. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

