<F P=100> MEXICO </F>
<H3> <TI>   PRI President Denies Presidential Aspirations </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA2903152094 Mexico City Canal 13 Television Azteca Network 
in Spanish 1400 GMT 29 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA2903152094 </F>
<F P=104>  Mexico City Canal 13 Television Azteca Network 
in Spanish 1400 GMT 29 Mar 94 </F>



<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105>Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Speech by Fernando Ortiz Arana, president of the Mexican </F>
Institutional Revolutionary Party National Executive Committee, 
at the party's national headquarters in Mexico City; broadcast 
in progress -- live] 
  [Text] ...a document that contains a decision by the 
president of the National Executive Committee [CEN], of which I 
have already given an account to the CEN itself. As a member 
and especially as a leader of the PRI [Institutional 
Revolutionary Party] my ethical responsibility and personal 
convictions have forced me to make the following statement: 
  It is the fundamental responsibility of the president of the 
PRI-CEN to maintain the PRI's unity and guide its forces in 
accordance with the fundamental principles and values that we 
have always maintained. Under such circumstances, any conduct 
motivated by personal ambitions could cause divisions within the 
party. To allow this would be very serious and irresponsible, to 
encourage it would betray the party's traditional order. 
  The death of our friend and comrade, Luis Donaldo Colosio, 
has generated unprecedented conditions for the party. Luis 
Donaldo was an exemplary member of the PRI; his pledges will 
continue to be ours. His proposals of change with security and 
responsibility will continue to be our political undertaking. 
Nothing better than this undertaking to keep his democratic 
example and his guiding presence alive. Thus, I consider it my 
unavoidable duty to say that as the PRI national leader I do not 
aspire to be nominated as a candidate to the presidency of the 
Republic. To aspire to such a nomination from the position I 
hold within the party would be disloyal to the political 
institution to which I owe unwavering adherence and fidelity. To 
do that would be to take advantage of a situation and it would 
thus be unacceptable. Such an aspiration would also violate my 
personal convictions and the pledge I made when I took the oath 
as president of the party's CEN. 
  No action is minor in the effort to strengthen and fortify 
our party. The PRI's traditional roots and basic elements 
demand that each of its members and leaders zealously fulfill 
their duty to keep the party solid and strong. Any dispersion of 
the PRI's forces will constitute a serious risk to the party's 
unity and stability, especially now, when it is absolutely 
necessary for us to close ranks around our principles, 
loyalties, institutions, laws, and President Carlos Salinas de 
Gortari. Nothing is more important for a member of the PRI -- 
and more so for the president of the PRI -- than to preserve and 
strengthen the value that the party's unity has always held for 
us. The president of the PRI must not lean in anyone's favor, 
let alone in his own favor. That is all, gentlemen. Thank you 
very much. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

