<F P=100> Venezuela </F>
<H3> <TI>   Carabobo Governor Requests Support on Draft of Election Law </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA2803170194 Caracas Venezolana de Television Network in 
Spanish 2350 GMT 24 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA2803170194 </F>
<F P=104>  Caracas Venezolana de Television Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From "The News" newscast] </F>
  [Text] Enrique Salas Romer, Carabobo State governor, has 
requested support from the various parliamentary wings so that 
the Chamber of Deputies will label as urgent the draft law for 
reforming the Law on the Election and Removal of Governors. 
Raina Rondon reports from Congress. 
  [Begin recording] [Rondon] In the afternoon, Governor Salas 
Romer already had the support of the Democratic Action [AD], 
Copei [Social Christian Party], and MAS [Movement Toward 
Socialism parliamentary wings], support he feels guarantees the 
draft reform will be submitted to Congress within the next few 
days. 
  [Salas Romer] Based on Article 22 of the Constitution--which 
establishes that Congress will issue a law on the election and 
removal of governors--it is possible to establish the conditions 
within which one could go to the extreme of dismissing the 
governor. 
  [Rondon] Meanwhile, Antonio Ledezma has announced Congress 
decided during the session to declare the health sector in a 
state of emergency due to the serious hospital crisis prevailing 
throughout the country and the doctors' conflict. 
  Gustavo Tarre Briceno, chairman of the lower chamber Finance 
Commission said Interior Minister Ramon Escovar Salom made a 
mistake when he said the Executive Branch would be willing to 
study a draft of a special powers law which will include 
mechanisms for resolving national social and administrative 
issues inasmuch as the Constitution establishes that special 
powers may only include economic and financial issues. 
  [Tarre Briceno] The government had not asked for anything up 
to now. AD comes and makes an offer. The executive branch, 
rather than accepting or rejecting that offer, now proposes, via 
the interior minister, more special powers to include 
administrative and social issues, which is evidently against the 
Constitution. 
  [Rondon] To conclude, Gustavo Tarre Briceno said Congress is 
only waiting for the executive branch to decide what it wants 
regarding the Special Powers law. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

