<F P=101> Argentina </F>
<H3> <TI>   Former De Facto President Acquitted of Charges </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PY2903211794 Buenos Aires BUENOS AIRES HERALD in English 29 
Mar 94 p 1 </F>

<F P=103> PY2903211794 </F>
<F P=104>  Buenos Aires BUENOS AIRES HERALD </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpt] (DYN-NA) -- Former de facto president, General 
Jorge Rafael Videla, was acquitted yesterday on charges of 
promoting crime filed against the former head of the military 
dictatorship after he had said that the Armed Forces should have 
been paid, instead of having to pay the price for their actions 
during the Dirty War. 
  According to the verdict issued by Judge Fernando Larrain, 
Videla did not intend to make his opinions public because they 
came in the context of a speech made at a dinner last year in 
front of some 50 retired military officers. 
  The complaint had been filed last November by the government 
through the Human Rights Under-Secretary Alicia Pierini after 
Videla's statements were reproduced by Buenos Aires daily 
CLARIN. Government sources yesterday refused to comment on the 
verdict. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

