<F P=100> INTER-AMERICAN AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Honduran Minister Comments </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA2903124194 Panama City ACAN in Spanish 2007 GMT 28 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> PA2903124194 </F>
<F P=104>  Panama City ACAN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tegucigalpa, 28 Mar (ACAN-EFE) -- Honduran Foreign 
Minister Ernesto Paz Aguilar today expressed his satisfaction 
with the election of Colombian President Cesar Gaviria as OAS 
secretary general. 
  Paz told Voz de Honduras radio station in a telephone 
interview from Washington that the nomination of Gaviria "we 
believe was the result of a democratic election in which the law 
of the majority prevailed, which is the fundamental law of 
democracy." "Gaviria won as a result, and we believe he is a 
hemispheric leader who will give proper leadership to the OAS," 
he said. The minister added that among the majority of the OAS 
member countries there is "satisfaction," but he also said "the 
feeling of bitterness, especially that of Costa Rican Foreign 
Minister Bernd Niehaus," is logical. 
  Niehaus made an intense but unfortunate effort because in 
democracy there is always a winner and a loser, according to 
Paz, who pointed out that Gaviria defeated the Costa Rican 
foreign minister in the first round 20 votes to 14. 
  Honduras' position on the election of the OAS secretary 
general was to support the Costa Rican candidate, Bernd Niehaus, 
in the first round and Gaviria in the second round. Paz Aguilar 
said that Honduras promised to support a Central American 
candidacy because it "respects the promises that were made;" 
however, he refused to comment on the change of heart of those 
who had pledged their support for Niehaus. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-12043 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drlat061_b_94002" </HT>


