<F P=100> MEXICO </F>
<H3> <TI>   Candidate Zedillo's Professional Career Reviewed </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA2903194494 Mexico City NOTIMEX in Spanish 1815 GMT 29 Mar 
94 </F>

<F P=103> PA2903194494 </F>
<F P=104>  Mexico City NOTIMEX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Mexico City, 29 Mar (NOTIMEX) -- Today, the 
Institutional Revolutionary Party's [PRI] National Political 
Council designated Ernesto Zedillo Ponce de Leon as its new 
candidate for president. Zedillo Ponce de Leon was born in 
Mexico City on 27 December 1951. He is the son of Rodolfo 
Zedillo Castillo and Martha Alicia Ponce de Leon. He is the 
second of six brothers, after Luis. Following him came 
Guadalupe, Lorena, Veronica, and Rodolfo. He is married to 
Nilda Patricia Velasco Nunez and is the father of five children: 
Ernesto, Emiliano, Carlos, Nilda Patricia, and Rodrigo. 
  Zedillo holds a B.S. degree from the National Politechnical 
Institute's Higher School of Economy, where he studied from 
1969-72. He also studied economics at the University of 
Colorado in 1974. He received a master's degree and a doctoral 
degree in economics from Yale University, which he attended from 
1974-78. His doctoral thesis was entitled: "External Public 
Indebtedness in Mexico: Recent History and Future Oil Bounded 
Optical Growth." [thesis title as received in English] 
  He worked as an economic researcher in the Secretariat of 
the 
Presidency's National Directorate for Economic and Social 
Programming from 1971-74, as an economist with the Bank of 
Mexico from 1978-82, and as deputy manager for economic and 
financial research in the same bank in 1982. He was secretary 
for programming and budget from 1988-92. In 1992, he was named 
secretary for public education, a post from which he resigned on 
29 November 1993 in order to join the campaign of the now 
deceased PRI candidate Luis Donaldo Colosio. 
  He was a professor at the Colegio de Mexico from 1981-83. He 
distinguished himself with his economic studies, which in turn 
led to his appointment as secretary for programming and budget. 
He outlined the National Development Plan, which has led to 
important political, economic, and social changes during the 
government of President Carlos Salinas de Gortari. With the 
motto "Planning Is Prevention," Zedillo outlined the government 
strategies established since 1988 to date and within whose 
framework the government drafted programs to lower inflation by 
reducing spending, resuming growth, and attaining steady 
progress in the economic recovery. 
  As the person responsible for the proposals dealing with 
1989, 1990, and 1991 disbursements, he appeared before the 
Chamber of Deputies and corresponding commissions on several 
occasions, where he mounted an imprtant defense of the budgets 
and the National Solidarity Program. Zedillo also participated 
in laying the groundwork for the national agreements on the 
country's modernization, which led to an increase in several 
special allocations for agriculture and education. 
  While he was secretary for programming and budget, Zedillo 
pursued dialogue, negotiation, and harmony with all governors, 
including those in opposition. Later, when he was secretary for 
public education, he subscribed to the thesis that "the higher 
the education, the greater the wealth," which held that the 
country's modernization was not just "fashionable" but an 
essential requirement in raising the country to the level of 
advanced countries with an eye on the 21st Century. In this 
context, he negotiated and secured approval for changes to 
Article 3 of the Constitution. He had the Congress approve a 
new General Education Law as an essential measure in meeting the 
challenge of the country's education with the new millenium in 
mind. Progress made in education during Zedillo's tenure 
crystallized in a national plan for the modernization of basic 
education, reform providing for free textbooks, and the reform 
of teachers' career tracks. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

