<F P=100> MEXICO </F>
<H3> <TI>   PRD Spokesman: Zedillo To Focus on Economic Issues </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA2903215494 Madrid EFE in Spanish 1954 GMT 29 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> PA2903215494 </F>
<F P=104>  Madrid EFE </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Mexico City, Federal District, 29 Mar (EFE) -- 
Today, the opposition Party of the Democratic Revolution (PRD) 
said the new ruling party presidential candidate, Ernesto 
Zedillo Ponce de Leon, will give priority to economic issues and 
will relegate social issues. PRD spokesman Julio Ulloa said the 
campaign of the late Institutional Revolutionary Party (PRI) 
candidate, Luis Donaldo Colosio, was characterized by its 
inclination to address social problems such as poverty. "This 
new candidate totally changes the focus of the electoral 
campaign. Colosio had focused on social issues as has the PRD 
government program," he pointed out. The spokesman added that 
because of the post he held in the government, Zedillo's 
campaign will apparently focus on economic issues and their 
social repercussions. 
  Since November 1993, Zedillo had been a coordinator for PRI 
candidate Luis Donaldo Colosio's campaign, who was assassinated 
on 23 March in Tijuana on the U.S. border. Colosio had realized 
that addressing poverty was a priority of the times, but this 
will most probably be placed in the middle level of importance 
by the new candidate although he will continue the programs of 
the current government. Ulloa added that the new candidate will 
make the differences between the campaigns of the PRI and PRD, 
the country's third electoral force, more evident. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

