<F P=100> MEXICO </F>
<H3> <TI>   Former Policeman Arrested in Colosio Murder Case </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA2903192194 Madrid EFE in Spanish 1807 GMT 29 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> PA2903192194 </F>
<F P=104>  Madrid EFE </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Mexico City, 29 Mar (EFE) -- Today, the Attorney 
General's Office (PRG) accused former policeman Tranquilino 
Sanchez Venegas of complicity in the murder of Luis Donaldo 
Colosio, PRI [Institutional Revolutionary Party] presidential 
candidate. The murder occurred on 23 March in Tijuana. 
  Sanchez Venegas was arrested on Saturday. He then gave his 
deposition to the Attorney General's Office. Today, in federal 
court, he was accused of alleged complicity. The suspicion that 
he participated in the murder is based on an analysis of the 
videotape broadcast on television and on graphic material in the 
police's possession where it appears that Sanchez Venegas, while 
watching, opened a path through the crowd for the murderer, 
without acting to prevent it, as confessed murderer Mario Aburto 
Martinez shoots Colosio in the right temple. 
  Various PRG officials, who asked to remain anonymous, 
indicated that the arrest of the former policeman was made after 
a lady friend of Aburto Martinez declared that on 11 March the 
two individuals met in a Tijuana park. According to official 
reports, the former policeman was employed by the Tijuana PRI 
for "crowd control" at the event were Colosio was murdered. 
  Colosio was murdered on 23 March in Tijuana as he was 
concluding an event in his electoral campaign. The candidate was 
shot in the stomach and in the head. This resulted in instant 
brain death. Three hours later he died. The alleged murderer is 
being held at the Almoloya jail in Juarez, Mexico's maxiumum 
security jail. He is expected to be tried in the coming weeks 
once the investigation concludes. The PRG has indicated that for 
now, no one else has been arrested as an accomplice in the 
murder, although several individuals are being investigated. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-12072 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drlat061_c_94011" </HT>


