<F P=100> Guatemala </F>
<H3> <TI>   Government, URNG Reach Agreement </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA2903230494 Guatemala City Teleonce Television in Spanish 
1900 GMT 29 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA2903230494 </F>
<F P=104>  Guatemala City Teleonce Television </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Willy Melgar; from the "Telepress" newscast] </F>
  [Text] [Words indistinct] repeated reports on an attack 
perpetrated in the country's interior during the past days, the 
[words indistinct] announcement in Puebla, Mexico on agreements 
reached by the government and the guerrillas within the 
framework of the dialogue started in 1991. 
  Mexican President Carlos Salinas de Gortari and Guatemalan 
President Ramiro de Leon Carpio might attend the signing of the 
human rights agreement reached by the Guatemalan Government and 
the URNG [Guatemalan National Revolutionary Unity], according to 
sources in Mexico's Foreign Relations Secretariat. 
  The parties reached preagreement points in the overall human 
rights accord. Among them are promises to: 

  -  Guarantee and protect the basic rules [preceptos]; 
  -  Fight impunity, and for this purpose, promote the necessary 
modifications of the Penal Code; 
  -  Strengthen democratic institutions; 
  -  Attain immediate international verification; 
  -  Institute voluntary military recruitment; 
  -  Fight against any evidence of illegal corps in the country; 
and 
  -  Compensate the victims of human rights violations. 

    It was reported that the URNG invited Monsignor Rodolfo 
Quezada, conciliator for life of the process, Teresa de [word 
indistinct], and other personalities of Guatemalan civilian 
society to attend this ceremony. It was also reported that in 
this round of talks there was consensus on the establishment of 
a timetable for the agreements reached in Mexico on 26 April 
1991. 
  The Mutual Support Group [GAM] today issued a statement on 
the establishment of a Truth Commission in reaction to the news 
of the agreements reached in Puebla, Mexico, during the last 
round of talks between the government and the guerrillas. The 
GAM document states: Guatemalans are experiencing times of hope 
by knowing that the government, Army, and URNG decided to hold 
talks and find political solutions to the internal armed 
conflict that was produced by the profound inequalities that 
exist in the country. It is evident that we have talked about 
two Guatemalans historically: one of Spanish-Indian descent 
[ladina] and the other Indian. We must definitely learn to 
integrate into a single nation with a [word indistinct] sense, 
while respecting diversity, but working in the same direction 
and with the same objective -- to turn Guatemala into a homeland 
for all. 
  The document adds: [Words indistinct] to the extent that we 
seriously correct the mistakes of the past, which we all 
committed by action or omission. (?This is no time) to analyze 
who is to blame for the systematic and repeated problems that 
led to their accumulation. The truth is that there was a wall 
of silence and this nourished all those who had thoughts that 
went against the state of things. What has been established is 
not necessarily the rule to follow; there are options. 
  It further states: History (?zealously) teaches us, who 
remember it, that those who acted with impunity in the years of 
the repression will continue to do so. They (?built) a strong 
structure, which will be difficult to dismantle, and today are 
deciding the fate of the country at all levels through different 
methods but with the same results. 
  Thus, the document adds, it is imperative and indispensable 
to create conditions for the Truth or Investigative Commission. 
This, however, must not be a pantomime to get out of trouble. 
A document specifying that there will finally be a cease-fire 
should be signed. The Truth or Investigative Commission should 
be precisely that: a commission to deal with the truth 
regardless of the influence that a civilian, soldier, or 
insurgent, who killed defenseless and unarmed citizens with 
impunity, might have. We are therefore not referring to those 
from one party or the other who have fallen in the crossfire. 
  It states: We clearly specify that we are talking about the 
Guatemalans who were kidnapped, murdered, or massacred by 
uniformed paramilitary groups while at home or walking on the 
streets. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-12081 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drlat061_g_94003" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-LAT-94-061 </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  29 Mar 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> Guatemala </F>
<H3> <TI>   President Pleased With Accord </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA2903202694 Panama City ACAN in Spanish 1851 GMT 29 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> PA2903202694 </F>
<F P=104>  Panama City ACAN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Guatemala City, 29 Mar (ACAN-EFE) -- Guatemalan 
President Ramiro De Leon Carpio today expressed satisfaction 
over the general [global] human rights agreement his government 
reached with the guerrillas at a meeting in Puebla, Mexico. 
  "I believe all Guatemalans should be pleased with the 
progress made in the negotiations process," the head of state 
said on Radio "Sonora." 
  De Leon explained that he cannot express any opinions 
concerning the agreement because he pledged not to do so during 
the talks. Only the UN moderator, Frenchman Jean Arnault, can 
provide details. 
  Nevertheless, he emphasized that "considerable progress has 
been made" with the signing of the general agreement on human 
rights which excludes the Truth Commission, which was formed to 
investigate violations of individual guarantees throughout the 
34 years of the armed conflict. 
  The president said that he and the Armed Forces High 
Command, 
which he also heads, have been in permanent contact with the 
National Commission for the Consolidation of Peace (COPAZ) 
presided over by Hector Rosada, examining each of the points as 
they were agreed upon. 
  "We have been fully informed, and we ought to be pleased 
because considerable progress has been made," de Leon stressed. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-12082 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drlat061_g_94004" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-LAT-94-061 </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  29 Mar 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> Guatemala </F>
<H3> <TI>   Leaders React to Accord </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA2903223794 Panama City ACAN in Spanish 1731 GMT 29 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> PA2903223794 </F>
<F P=104>  Panama City ACAN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Guatemala City, 29 Mar (ACAN-EFE) -- The agreement 
on human rights reached in Mexico by the Guatemalan Government 
and the guerrillas is the greatest outcome in three years of 
negotiations and opens the possibility for President Ramiro de 
Leon Carpio to meet his objective of pacifying the nation. 
  The former human rights ombudsman -- who became Guatemala's 
president on 6 June 1993 in the midst of a terrible political 
crisis originated by ousted President Jorge Serrano's failed 
self-coup -- has paved the way to peace with the signing of an 
overall agreement on human rights with the rebels. 
  The Government Peace Commission (Copaz) and the Guatemalan 
National Revolutionary Unity's (URNG) "military command" reached 
this agreement in Puebla (Mexico) after overcoming several 
obstacles throughout three years of conversations. 
  The agreement with the rebels strengthens Ramiro de Leon 
Carpio's administration, which during his 10 months in power has 
lost credibility and the support of the diverse sectors of 
society that demand an end to the conflict and better living 
conditions. People's leaders consulted by ACAN-EFE indicated 
that light can now be seen at the end of the tunnel and that 
even though the agreement has been signed true hope lies in its 
fulfillment and the beginning of the end of the massacre. 
  "The signing of the agreement is a victory for the whole 
community that pressured the government and the guerrillas. It 
is not a voluntary gift, although it fell on Ramiro de Leon 
Carpio," stressed Rosario Pu, leader of the Committee of Peasant 
Unity (CUC). 
  Meanwhile, Rosalina Tuyuc, leader of the National Commission 
of Guatemalan Widows (Conavigua), told ACAN-EFE that a first 
step has been taken for a constitution of civilian communities 
[pueblos civiles] and that this agreement will stimulate and 
support the people. "For us the signing of this accord is very 
important because it opens up a space for society," she 
highlighted. 
  Meanwhile, Human Rights Ombudsman Jorge Mario Garcia 
Laguardia said the agreement gives "a new glimmer of hope to the 
population" because the parties have demonstrated their 
democratic calling to reach an understanding. Garcia recognized 
that the work of Frenchman Jean Arnault was a key to reaching 
the accord, with which the incipient democracy will be 
strengthened in the medium- and long-term. For the human rights 
ombudsman now "it is necessary to form a national front of peace 
to discuss an agreement of social conditions as the only way to 
end the instability." 
  Nineth Montenegro, president of the Mutual Support Group 
(GAM), also told ACAN-EFE that after 34 years of war the 
agreement represents "a significant step forward" in the 
attainment of peace. "I am very happy to hear there is talk of 
democratizing and demilitarizing the country," the human rights 
leader remarked. 
  The issue of human rights was the most complex one of the 11 
points on the agenda agreed upon in Mexico in 1991 by the 
government and the URNG under the mediation of Catholic Bishop 
Rodolfo Quezada Toruno. According to Quezada Toruno, who was 
dismissed from the negotiations by de Leon Carpio, who in turned 
requested the UN mediation, under his mediation the parties were 
nearing the signing of an accord, but the foiled coup 
perpetrated by Serrano on 25 May 1993 ruined all the efforts. 
  The peace negotiations became bogged down several times 
during the coupist government of Serrano, and although de Leon 
gave new momentum to the process, it was not until last January 
that his representatives were able to meet for the first time 
with rebel leaders in Mexico. 
  De Leon removed the main players of the government in the 
process and appointed Hector Rosada to head the government 
delegation. Rosada has been charged with exerting pressure to 
force Quezada Toruno's removal and dissolve the National 
Reconciliation Commission. 
  The signing of the human rights accord and its international 
verification mark the end of a 34-year-old armed confrontation 
in Guatemala, the only country in Central America where tension 
remains. The undeclared civil war has left more than 150,000 
people dead, some 250,000 widows, and 45,000 missing persons due 
to political reasons, as well as thousands of refugees. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

