<F P=102>  PA2903175394 </F>
<F P=103> PA2903175394 </F>
<F P=104></F>



<TEXT>
Article   Type:BFN 

  [Editorial Report] Managua BARRICADA in Spanish on 23 March 
on pages 1 and 5 reports that Central Bank President Evenor 
Taboada has announced that the Government of Nicaragua has 
agreed to reduce public spending by more than 4 percentage 
points of the GDP, as demanded by the IMF as a condition for 
signing the Enhanced Structural Adjustment Facility (ESAF). 
Taboada added that figures show Nicaragua must transfer 
resources from the public sector to the private sector, while 
guaranteeing stability and the growth of the economy. 

