<F P=100> Peru </F>
<H3> <TI>   Foreign Minister Visits Malaysia, Seeks Investment </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PY3003010594 Lima EL PERUANO in Spanish 23 Mar 94 p A3 </F>
<F P=103> PY3003010594 </F>
<F P=104>  Lima EL PERUANO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Yesterday, Foreign Minister Efrain Goldenberg 
Schreiber, president of the Council of Ministers, said that 
Peru's geographical diversity plus recent changes in investment 
and commerce laws are important advantages that it can offer 
investors over other Pacific basin nations. Goldenberg today 
participated in the first day of sessions of the 10th General 
Conference of the Pacific Economic Cooperation Council (PECC). 
  Goldenberg was the first speaker at the conference's opening 
meeting in Kuala Lumpur, the capital of Malaysia. The conference 
will continue today with discussions on capital and financial 
markets in Latin America. Goldenberg will be the main speaker. 
He stressed that Peru has Amazon and Andean regions and a long 
Pacific Ocean coastline. He said this is an interesting option 
for investors. 
  He met yesterday with government officials present at the 
conference. He talked with Malaysian Prime Minister Datuk Sri 
Dr. Mahathir bin Mohamed and with the U.S. Security Council 
Asian affairs senior adviser with whom he reviewed prospects for 
regional cooperation, promotion, and investment. Goldenberg also 
met with the Indonesian representative. He delivered a Peruvian 
Government invitation to President Suharto to visit Peru. 
  During today's session, besides the discussion on capital 
and 
financial markets in Latin America, there will be a forum on 
international commerce that will be presided over by Eduardo 
Ferrero Costa, a member of the Peruvian delegation and head of 
the Peruvian National Committee for the Pacific Basin. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

