<F P=100> INTER-AMERICAN AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Ecuadoran Minister Pleased With Gaviria Victory </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA3003025194 Mexico City NOTIMEX in Spanish 2144 GMT 28 Mar 
94 </F>

<F P=103> PA3003025194 </F>
<F P=104>  Mexico City NOTIMEX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Quito, 28 Mar (NOTIMEX) -- Ecuadoran Foreign 
Minister Diego Paredes expressed satisfaction today over the 
election of Colombian President Cesar Gaviria as OAS secretary 
general. 
  In a message issued at the OAS office in Washington, Paredes 
said he is "proud to have supported the Colombian president's 
candidacy, given the exceptional relationship between our two 
countries. We are proud because our support has been a 
demonstration and a reflection of the sentiments of affection 
the Ecuadoran people have toward Colombia and its president, 
Cesar Gaviria." 
  In February the government of Ecuadoran President Sixto 
Duran-Ballen announced its commitment to support the Costa Rican 
candidate, Foreign Minister Bernd Niehaus. Ecuador maintained 
its support for Costa Rica until a few days before the election. 
Last Friday [25 March] it changed its position in favor of the 
Colombian candidate, who was elected Sunday [27 March] with 20 
votes. Niehaus received 14 votes. 
  In his message, Paredes also congratulated the Costa Rican 
candidate "for his lofty and dignified campaign." He said it was 
a pleasure for the Ecuadoran delegation to adhere to the 
expressions of affection and recognition of the work carried out 
by outgoing OAS Secretary General Joao Baena Soares, who has 
headed the organization for the past 10 years. 
  [Madrid EFE in Spanish at 2130 GMT on 28 March carries a 
report saying that "the Ecuadoran Government expressed surprise 
today over Colombia's economic measures against Ecuadoran 
exporters and stressed that the announcement was made when 
Ecuador `gave its clear and definitive support to (Colombian) 
President Cesar Gaviria's candidacy for OAS secretary general.'"] 

</TEXT>

