<F P=100> Colombia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Oil for Cuba Conditioned on Payment Guarantees </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA2903211094 Santa Fe de Bogota Emisoras Caracol Network in 
Spanish 1200 GMT 27 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA2903211094 </F>
<F P=104>  Santa Fe de Bogota Emisoras Caracol Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Santa Fe de Bogota -- The lack of payment guarantees 
could cause negotiations for oil sales between Colombia and Cuba 
to fail. According to the government, sales might be possible 
only if Cuba complies with conditions established by Ecopetrol 
[Colombian Petroleum Enterprise] for the sale of crude on the 
international markets. A spokesman for the [word indistinct] 
ministry said no concessions will be made. 
  According to official sources, Cuba has offered to cover the 
cost of the negotiations with sugar, in a three-party 
transaction that is not acceptable to Colombia. The island 
government would reportedly sell sugar -- the island's main 
source of currency -- at low prices to a third country. That 
nation, which has not been further identified, would resell the 
sugar on the international market. With the proceeds from the 
sale, this nation would then pay Colombia for the oil sold to 
Cuba. 
  An official spokesman said: We prefer a letter of credit. As 
long as there are no payment guarantees, there will be no 
negotiations. He explained that until now President Castro's 
government has not made another proposal. The failure of the 
negotiations, which are now practically suspended, would not be 
due to international pressures exerted after the negotiations 
were announced but because Ecopetrol's conditions for 
negotiations of this type have not been met, the government said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-12116 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drlat062_a_94001" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-LAT-94-062 </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  31 Mar 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> CARIBBEAN </F>
<F P=101> Cuba </F>
<H3> <TI>   Colombian Newspaper Publishes Castro's Letter </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  FL3103022994 Havana Tele Rebelde and Cuba Vision Networks in 
Spanish 0100 GMT 31 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> FL3103022994 </F>
<F P=104>  Havana Tele Rebelde and Cuba Vision Networks </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Today, the newspaper EL TIEMPO in Bogota, Colombia, 
published a letter from Cuban President Fidel Castro who 
acknowledges the paper's apologies for publishing reports on a 
supposed guerrilla meeting in Cuba. In his letter, which is 
addressed to the newspaper's editor and which was published on 
the front page of the largest Colombian newspaper, the head of 
the Cuban Revolution states that the issue is important and 
serious. The letter adds that the incident could have had 
serious and undesirable repercussions both for the credibility 
of many people and for [words indistinct]. 
  In his letter to the Colombian newspaper EL TIEMPO, Fidel 
Castro added that he considers it his duty to express his most 
sincere appreciation for the step taken to deny reports 
published by the same newspaper that were not in keeping with 
the truth, and for the apology to Monsignor Nel Beltran and the 
Cuban Government. 
  Fidel Castro notes that in explaining the incident and 
apologizing to those affected, the newspaper EL TIEMPO has shown 
courage and honesty. We admit this, Fidel Castro said in his 
letter. He added: We accept your apologies and congratulate you, 
the newspaper's board, and the reporters and workers for an 
attitude that exalts us. 
  Fidel Castro concludes his letter to the newspaper EL TIEMPO 
in Bogota, Colombia, with an expression of hope and expectation 
that we will all learn a useful lesson from the unpleasant 
incident and that mutual respect and relations between the 
peoples of Cuba and Colombia will be strengthened. 

</TEXT>

