<F P=100> Haiti </F>
<H3> <TI>   Peace Plan: Aristide Insists on Military Step-Down </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  FL3003174094 Port-au-Prince Signal FM Radio in French 1130 
GMT 30 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> FL3003174094 </F>
<F P=104>  Port-au-Prince Signal FM Radio </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> French </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpt] Exiled Haitian President Jean-Bertrand Aristide 
has rejected the new U.S. plan aimed at restoring him to power, 
insisting on the need for the military in power to resign as the 
first step of a peace plan in Haiti. It is this strategy that 
will lead to the restoration of democracy in Haiti, Aristide 
explained in a communique issued on 29 March. 
  Aristide was responding to the new U.S. initiative providing 
for the simultaneous appointment of a new prime minister and the 
resignation of the current military government in 
Port-au-Prince, which would get amnesty. This plan also provides 
for strengthening the international trade embargo by reinforcing 
the watch over the border between Haiti and the Dominican 
Republic in order to increase pressure on the military regime. 
  Father Aristide, who was informed of this new plan on 25 
March by U.S. Vice President Al Gore, pointed out that he is 
sticking to the eight-point plan that he presented to the United 
Nations in October. The exiled president has added that if the 
military gives up power on the morning [of any given day], he 
will appoint a prime minister that very afternoon. [passage 
omitted] 

</TEXT>

