<F P=100> ARAB AFRICA </F>
<F P=101> Egypt </F>
<H3> <TI>   Dailies, Commentaries React to Hebron `Massacre' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  NC2602070994 Cairo MENA in Arabic 2200 GMT 25 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC2602070994 </F>
<F P=104>  Cairo MENA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Arabic </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Cairo, 25 Feb (MENA)--Cairo dailies in their 26 
February editions highlight the horrendous crime a Jewish 
settler committed in the city of Hebron in the occupied West 
Bank. The dailies dedicate their front page headlines to reports 
on the tragedy. 
  Draped in black, AKHBAR AL-YAWM's headline says "Massacre in 
the Ibrahimi Mosque." 
  In its commentary, the paper says that the goal of the 
Israeli extremists was to deal a fatal blow to peace. It adds 
that this massacre should not pass unnoticed; we should pause 
long over it to ask Israel and the world many questions that 
need answering: What is meant by preserving security in the 
Middle East region? Is it Israel's security alone? Where is 
the Palestinians' security? And is it reasonable to leave the 
destiny of the honorable Jerusalem in the hands of Israeli 
extremists who determine who enters it and who gets out, who 
lives and who dies? 
  AKHBAR AL-YAWM says that every Muslim and Christian in the 
world must strongly condemn this barbaric crime. The world 
should not content itself with condemnations; it should seek 
ways to return holy places to their owners instead of leaving 
them in the hands of those who cannot protect them and who let 
armed extremists and crazy persons kill innocent people at dawn, 
AKHBAR AL-YAWM says. 
  In its editorial, AL-AHRAM says this dreadful massacre is, 
first and foremost, the responsibility of the Israeli 
Government. It is not possible to claim that a crazy settler 
committed it of his own accord. 
  The paper notes that there are precedents that fall into the 
same category. Israel claimed that the person who set fire to 
the al- Aqsa Mosque before was mentally unstable, AL-AHRAM says, 
adding that a number of Palestinian laborers working in Israel 
were killed a few years back and the Israeli authorities claimed 
that the murderer was mentally unstable. 
  The paper asks if Palestinian blood has become so cheap that 
dozens of fasting Palestinians should be killed as they 
performed dawn prayers at the Ibrahimi Mosque. Is it reasonable 
that the Israeli Government's only reaction should be just a 
statement appealing to Palestinians not to take revenge, the 
paper asks. 
  AL-AHRAM affirms that Egypt will take a clear-cut stand when 
the UN Security Council considers this barbaric aggression. 
  AL-JUMHURIYAH's main headline says "The Martyrdom of 61 
Palestinians in the Ibrahimi Mosque." 
  The paper highlights Egypt's condemnation of this heinous 
massacre and Palestinian President Yasir 'Arafat's call for an 
emergency meeting of the UN Security Council to take the proper 
measures to protect the Palestinian people. 
  In its editorial, AL-JUMHURIYAH writes that this massacre 
will burden the international community with the big 
responsibility of insuring security for the Palestinian people, 
who suffer daily as a result of the Israeli occupation practices. 
  The paper adds that this massacre once again emphasizes the 
need to use fair logic, observe human rights, and implement the 
international resolutions that call for Israel's withdrawal from 
the occupied Arab territories and for protecting the 
Palestinians' right to confront the unheeding, continuous 
Israeli oppression that goes on with the support and 
encouragement of the United States, which is keen to supply the 
Israeli Army with the most sophisticated weapons. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

