<F P=100> ISRAEL </F>
<H3> <TI>   Cabinet Members Holds Special, Regular Meetings </TI></H3>
<H4>   Special Meeting Ends </H4>
<F P=102> TA2502163294 Jerusalem Qol Yisra'el in Hebrew 1600 GMT 25 
Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> TA2502163294 </F>
<F P=104>  Jerusalem Qol Yisra'el </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Hebrew </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] The special cabinet meeting ended in Tel Aviv a 
short while ago. The ministers raised proposals for the prime 
minister's attention and consideration. These proposals will be 
worked out by the prime minister and then raised for discussion 
at the cabinet meeting on 27 February. One proposal was to 
remove dangerous residents if there is evidence that they are 
Kakh members. Another was to pay compensation to the casualties. 
A third proposal was to establish a national inquiry commission. 
  Minister Binyamin Ben-Eli'ezer told our correspondent 
Karmela 
Menashe that the government is determined to accelerate the 
peace process. Minister Amnon Rubinstein noted that for the 
first time, a closure was imposed also on Jewish residents in 
Hebron and Qiryat Arba' and that they cannot move without 
permission. 
  At the end of the meeting, Police Minister Moshe Shahal said 
that the police are currently operating in 12-hour shifts. 
Units were reinforced in all sensitive places, particularly in 
Jerusalem. The police minister added that the attorney general 
raised several proposals during the meeting, including removing 
Jewish residents from their homes, a move which according to the 
attorney general, has a legal basis. 
  Our correspondent Moti Amir reports the closure was expanded 
to encompass the whole of Judaea and Samaria, and to close down 
the Cave of the Patriarchs for 48 hours. The closure on the 
Gaza Strip, imposed this morning, as well the curfew imposed on 
Hebron and Bethlehem following the murder, are continuing. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

