<F P=100> ISRAEL </F>
<H3> <TI>   Cabinet Members Holds Special, Regular Meetings </TI></H3>
<H4>   Announcement After Special Meeting </H4>
<F P=102> TA2502180394 Jerusalem Israel Television Channel 1 Network 
in Arabic 1700 GMT 25 February 94 </F>

<F P=103> TA2502180394 </F>
<F P=104>  Jerusalem Israel Television Channel 1 Network 
in Arabic 1700 GMT 25 February 94 </F>



<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105>Arabic </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Government announcement following the cabinet meeting </F>
outside the prime minister's bureau at the government and Army 
compound in Tel Aviv on 25 February; read by Police Minister 
Moshe Shahal in Hebrew -- recorded] 
  [Text] The government's decision following today's debate, 
a decision which the prime minister asked me and Minister Sarid 
to formulate, is as follows: 
  In its meeting today the cabinet expressed deep shock over 
the despicable murder of innocent Palestinians who were saying 
prayers, during the Ramadan fast, at the Cave of the Patriarchs, 
a place sacred to the two faiths. The government is sending its 
condolences to the families of the dead and is wishing speedy 
recovery to the wounded. The government has decided to 
compensate the families of the victims. The government is 
calling on all residents, both Arabs and Jews, to exercise 
maximum restraint despite the grave circumstances. The IDF 
[Israel Defense Forces] and all the security forces are adopting 
all necessary measures to prevent incitement, violence, and a 
deterioration of the situation. During the meeting, the cabinet 
ministers and the attorney general raised proposals for various 
possible measures of handling radical Israeli elements that are 
instigative elements in the territories. The government believes 
that these elements gravely and dangerously violate public 
order, and that every legal measure should be adopted to curb 
and restrain them. Even concerning an act by a single 
individual -- as was the case in Hebron this morning -- we 
cannot ignore the influence of instigative remarks made publicly 
that threaten the citizen's well-being. 
  The government has entrusted the prime minister and defense 
minister with the task of examining all measures proposed during 
today's discussion and of informing the cabinet of his decisions 
on 27 February. The investigation of today's incidents will be 
complete. The government is resolved to continue its peace 
efforts and to promote the negotiations to the best of its 
ability. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

