<F P=100> ISRAEL </F>
<H3> <TI>   Government Officials React To Hebron Incident </TI></H3>
<H4>   Minister Sees Talks Accelerating </H4>
<F P=102> NC2602095294 Paris AFP in English 0918 GMT 26 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC2602095294 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By Barry Parker] </F>
  [Excerpts] Jerusalem, Feb 26 (AFP) -- Israel and the PLO 
have pledged to turn the terrible carnage in a Hebron mosque 
into a catalyst for peace in fresh talks under US auspices next 
week. 
  "Paradoxically the tragedy leaves Israel and the PLO no 
alternative but to accelerate the peace negotiations so that the 
PLO can take control in the territories as soon as possible," an 
Israeli minister, who asked not to be named, told AFP. 
  Prime Minister Yitzhaq Rabin and PLO leader Yasir 'Arafat 
agreed to U.S. President Bill Clinton's appeal not to allow the 
massacre to undermine recent achievements and to hold new 
negotiations that will continue in Washington until a resolution 
is reached. 
  The minister said "damage control" contacts over the last 24 
hours between Israel and the PLO as well as with the Americans 
and Europeans had proved positive. 
  "Everyone agrees that we have to push ahead with peace," the 
minister said. "The negotiations could go very fast now." 
  There is no problem with the Palestinian leadership, what we 
fear is the Palestinian street. 
  "The coming days will be crucial. Things could get out of 
control in the territories." 
  For that reason, on top of international condemnation, 
Israel 
was under great pressure to come up with some real gestures such 
as an early release of Palestinian prisoners, to keep a lid on 
the violence, he said. Rabin was weighing his next move on 
Saturday, the minister added. 
  "The decision to punish the settlers by closing off Qiryat 
Arba' and to compensate Palestinian families is important. 
Symbolic measures such as closing off the killer's house or 
even blowing it up, as happens with the Palestinians, are under 
consideration," he revealed. 
  He said he hoped that ultimately the massacre could reduce 
the period of autonomy to under five years, allowing an early 
transition to a final settlement on the West Bank and Gaza 
Strip. [passage omitted] 
  Rabin pledged the killing would not halt the peace train. 
  "The crazy act of a pyschopath will not prevent the 
reconciliation between Israel and the Palestinians and will not 
stop the peace process," he vowed. 
  Foreign Minister Shim'on Peres added: "If anyone thinks such 
criminal acts will slow the peace efforts, they are sorely 
mistaken." [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

