<F P=100> ISRAEL </F>
<H3> <TI>   Government Officials React To Hebron Incident </TI></H3>
<H4>   Meretz, Aloni Urge Measures </H4>
<F P=102> TA2702094694 Jerusalem Qol Yisra'el in Hebrew 0900 GMT 27 
Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> TA2702094694 </F>
<F P=104>  Jerusalem Qol Yisra'el </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Hebrew </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Meretz demands that a state commission of inquiry 
be set up to investigate the incidents in Hebron, and that an 
Israeli Arab with legal education be a member of its board. 
  In the cabinet session today, Meretz ministers will demand 
that all the extreme settlers who advocate murder be arrested at 
once; that extremists be taken out of Tal al-Rumaydah, Hadassah 
House, and Romano House in the heart of Hebron; that the Army be 
instructed not to shoot at Palestinians in the territories; and 
that all that has so far been agreed on in the talks with the 
PLO be implemented at once. 
  Minister Shulamit Aloni told our correspondent Sheli 
Yehimovich that Meretz will also demand that the Kakh Movement 
be outlawed. According to her, we should make a distinction 
between idiots who speak out of their stupidity, and real 
instigators. She added that the remarks by Police Minister 
Moshe Shahal that the police are dealing with Arab and Jewish 
murderers along the same criteria are not true, and there is 
discrimination. 
  At the same time, she opposes the demand that the house of 
Barukh Goldstein be sealed, just as she opposes sealing the 
homes of Arabs. Minister Aloni added that the reserved 
condemnation of the Hebron massacre by the settler leaders 
borders on racism and viciousness. She added that Goldstein was 
not operating in a vacuum. In Israel, there is a nursery of 
Arab-hating racists who are after Arabs' lives and property, she 
said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-12182 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drnes039_l_94034" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-NES-94-039 </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  28 Feb 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> ISRAEL </F>
<H3> <TI>   Government Officials React To Hebron Incident </TI></H3>
<H4>   Beilin: U.S. Help Needed in Peace Talks </H4>
<F P=102> TA2802070394 Jerusalem Qol Yisra'el in Hebrew 0505 GMT 28 
Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> TA2802070394 </F>
<F P=104>  Jerusalem Qol Yisra'el </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Hebrew </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Telephone interview with Deputy Foreign Minister Yosi </F>
Beilin by Me'ir Einstein; place not given -- live] 
  [Text] [Einstein] Were you surprised by the Arab decision 
to suspend the talks? 
  [Beilin] It is hard to say that I was surprised but this is 
definitely a worrisome development which should not be 
disregarded. I think that the next step should be the United 
States getting into the thick of things in order to prevent any 
exacerbation that could ultimately present all the parties with 
a situation they may not have initially wanted. Such a 
development may, God forbid, preclude the continuation of the 
talks. 
  [Einstein] You speak of deeper U.S. involvement in the 
talks. Perhaps from our point of view this may lead to greater 
pressure on Israel? 
  [Beilin] No, definitely not. We are not worried about U.S. 
pressure on Israel. There is a high level of coordination 
between the United States and Israel. We know that the U.S. 
Administration is highly interested in promoting the peace 
process. On no account would the United States want the 
situation to deteriorate. Now, after this terrible act, Israel 
would have a hard time directly persuading the Syrians and 
Lebanese to return to the talks. We are also having a hard time 
with the PLO in this respect. I believe that right now the 
Americans could be helpful in this. 
  [Einstein] Deputy Foreign Minister Beilin, should Israel 
perhaps be more forthcoming toward the PLO, or were yesterday's 
cabinet decisions sufficient? 
  [Beilin] I believe that the decisions made yesterday 
constitute a precedent. Such decisions have never been taken 
before. 
  [Einstein] But nevertheless? 
  [Beilin] I do not see any room for additional decisions with 
regard to what happened in Hebron and the ramifications of that 
terrible deed. Israel can now tell the world that it has done 
all it could, and I very much hope that it will now be easier to 
resume the political process despite all the natural and 
understandable difficulties. 
  [Einstein] Thank you, Deputy Foreign Minister Beilin. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

