<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Inter-Arab Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Israel's `Procrastination' `Unacceptable' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  NC2802103594 Cairo MENA in Arabic 0950 GMT 28 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC2802103594 </F>
<F P=104>  Cairo MENA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Arabic </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpt] Cairo, 28 Feb (MENA)--Arab League Secretary 
General Dr. 'Ismat 'Abd-al-Majid has described the resolutions 
adopted by the emergency meeting of the Arab League Council last 
night as all-encompassing and comprehensive, revealing a united 
Arab stance that is rallying to condemn last Friday's ugly 
massacre in the Ibrahimi Mosque in Hebron in the occupied West 
Bank. 
  In statements today, Dr. 'Abd-al-Majid said the Arab League 
Council resolutions are a message from the Arab League to Israel 
and the international community, clarifying that prevarication, 
procrastination, and Israel's nonrespect for the dates agreed 
upon have become unacceptable in the Arab world. 
  He stressed that the Arab countries are seeking to achieve a 
comprehensive and just peace to create stability in the Middle 
East. He noted that peace is not only an Arab interest, but an 
Israeli one too. He said the Arabs want a just peace based on 
withdrawal from all the occupied Arab territories in accordance 
with the resolutions of international legitimacy and based on 
recognition of the Palestinian people's legitimate rights. 
  Dr. 'Abd-al-Majid went on to say that the Hebron massacre 
again highlighted the Arab stance that demands Israel's 
withdrawal from the occupied Arab territories, stressing that 
the Arab countries are not in a weak position, because justice 
is on their side. 
  He noted that the Palestinian intifadah activated the recent 
peace process and hastened the Madrid conference and the 
Washington peace talks. 
  The Arab League secretary general also stressed the 
importance of the Jerusalem issue. He said it has top priority 
in the negotiations and the Palestinian and Arab sides are 
determined to retrieve it. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

