<H3> <TI>   Arabs Suspend Washington Peace Talks After Hebron Shooting </TI></H3>
<H4>   Syrian Envoy Announces Suspension </H4>
<F P=102> JN2802063294 Paris Radio Monte Carlo in Arabic 0500 GMT 28 
Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> JN2802063294 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris Radio Monte Carlo </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Arabic </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Hisham Milhim dispatch from Washington] </F>
  [Excerpt] The Governments of Syria, Lebanon, and Jordan 
have decided to suspend bilateral peace negotiations with Israel 
in Washington before the end of the last week of talks on 
Wednesday. This decision is to put on record their vehement 
denunciation of the Ibrahimi Mosque massacre and to express 
their solidarity with the Palestinian people. 
  Syrian delegation head Muwaffaq al-'Allaf communicated this 
united Arab stand to peace negotiations coordinator Dennis Ross 
on Sunday afternoon. 
  Al-'Allaf told Radio Monte Carlo: In light of the 
circumstances resulting from the massacre, we found that it is 
not logical or suitable to pursue the negotiations. We also 
want to express our solidarity with the Palestinian people after 
this barbaric attack. 
  The suspension of negotiations takes place three days before 
they were scheduled to end. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

