<F P=100> JORDAN </F>
<H3> <TI>   Donation Campaign for Families of Victims Launched </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  JN2702213294 Amman Jordan Television Network in English 2000 
GMT 27 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> JN2702213294 </F>
<F P=104>  Amman Jordan Television Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "News at Ten" program] </F>
  [Text] Jordan has raised tens of thousands of dinars to 
support the victims of Friday's [25 February] Hebron Mosque 
massacre. His majesty the king had spearheaded a nationwide 
fundraising campaign and donated 100,000 dinars to support the 
families of the Palestinians killed by the Jewish settler. 
  The government announced a similar donation in addition to 
private donations from cabinet ministers, civil servants, 
deputies, and senators. 
  Three popular fundraising committees reported warm public 
response to calls for helping the victims' families. Amman 
Mayor Mamduh al-'Abbadi, who heads a popular committee helping 
the Palestinians, said it would give 1,000 dinars to each of the 
families of Palestinians killed in the mosque and the ensuing 
violence. He said the committee would also give 300 dinars to 
families of the Palestinians injured in the mosque massacre. 
  Mr. 'Abbadi told REUTERS that the committee offered to treat 
the Palestinian victims at Jordanian hospitals. 

</TEXT>

