<F P=100> Palestinian Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Al-Husayni Interviewed on Future of Peace Talks </TI></H3>
<H4>   Talks Should Focus on Final Settlement </H4>
<F P=102> TA2502190994 Jerusalem Israel Television Channel 1 Network 
in Arabic 1700 GMT 25 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> TA2502190994 </F>
<F P=104>  Jerusalem Israel Television Channel 1 Network 
in Arabic 1700 GMT 25 Feb 94 </F>



<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105>Arabic </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Interview with Faysal al-Husayni, chairman of the </F>
Palestinian delegation to the peace talks, by Fayiz 'Umar in 
Jerusalem on 25 February -- recorded] 
  [Text] [Al-Husayni] What happened, in fact, proves the 
gravity of the situation and that the presence of the Israeli 
Army or settlers in the occupied Palestinian territories is no 
longer relevant under any circumstances. What is happening now 
is a final destruction of the peace process. 
  ['Umar] As national institutions in the area, what sort of 
measures or decisions will you be adopting in the aftermath of 
this incident? 
  [Al-Husayni] First of all, we summoned the foreign consuls 
in Jerusalem to appraise them of the gravity of the situation 
and convey to them our position and demands, which began with 
disarming the settlers and providing international protection 
for the Palestinians. The Israeli Army is unable to do so. 
Apparently, it has a specific mission, which is only directed 
against the Palestinians and provides adequate cover to the 
settlers to do whatever they want. Hence, first of all we 
demand the disarming of the settlers; second, international 
protection; and third, other measures must follow to ensure 
Israeli withdrawal on the basis that no settlements will remain 
on Palestinian soil. 
  ['Umar] Do I understand from your remarks that you support 
Mr. 'Arafat's statement this morning, which he made after the 
incident? 
  [Al-Husayni] In fact, until now we have not received any 
details of this statement, but I believe that as far as the 
current peace process is concerned, modifications must be 
introduced in the agreements that have been reached. We have 
tried as much as possible to take a step forward, although not 
complete a one, in order to advance the peace process. However, 
what has happened today proves to us that such a step will not 
be fruitful. Now, we want the talks to deal with a final 
solution. We do not believe there is need for an interim stage, 
because an interim stage will lead to further bloodshed and 
losses. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-12263 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drnes039dd_94028" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-NES-94-039 </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  28 Feb 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> Palestinian Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Al-Husayni Interviewed on Future of Peace Talks </TI></H3>
<H4>   Says Settlements `Time Bomb' </H4>
<F P=102> NC2802072894 Cairo Voice of the Arabs in Arabic 0610 GMT 28 
Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> NC2802072894 </F>
<F P=104>  Cairo Voice of the Arabs </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Arabic </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Telephone interview with Faysal al-Husayni, chairman of the </F>
Palestinian delegation to the peace talks, in Jerusalem, by 
Ashraf 'Abd-al-'Aziz, in Cairo, on the "Dialogue From Afar" 
program; date not given--recorded] 
  [Text] ['Abd-al-'Aziz] Two days after the dreadful massacre 
committed against Palestinian citizens in the Ibrahimi Mosque, 
what is the situation in the occupied Arab territories? 
  [Al-Husayni] The Palestinians in Hebron, who were the 
victims 
of that massacre, are now living under a strict curfew; anyone 
who walks on the street is fired upon. The curfew is imposed on 
all other Palestinian towns: Bayt Sahur, Bayt Jala, Bethlehem, 
Ramallah, Nablus, Tulkarm, Qalqiliyah, and all the Palestinian 
towns and villages. People are moving freely in Qiryat Arba', 
the center where the crime was planned. Even the closure 
decision that the Israelis claim to have made is not in force; 
the area is not closed and the settlers are free to leave the 
settlement and return to it from Hebron and elsewhere. This 
shows the nature of the Israeli approach, which can only produce 
other such practices by the settlers--practices that the Israeli 
army completes, either by encouraging them or by participating 
in them. 
  ['Abd-al-'Aziz] There is more than one question about the 
implications of that criminal act. Was there really collusion 
between the Israeli Government or the Israeli army and the 
settlers? 
  [Al-Husayni] Israel's past approach created a particular 
Israeli mentality. This mentality is not necessarily exclusive 
to settlers; it can also extend to many of the Israeli soldiers, 
whose conduct is usually in line with what these settlers want. 
For instance, this settler killed 38 Palestinians inside the 
mosque. When the worshipers came running out of the mosque to 
escape the settler's fire, the army fired on them and killed 15. 
This mentality--incriminating the Palestinian just because he 
is Palestinian and always finding excuses for the Jew just 
because he is a Jew--is the core of the problem. This is what 
makes the existence of settlements the adversary of any attempt 
to achieve peace. We believe that the settlements' continuing 
presence is tantamount to a time bomb that will blow up among us 
at any minute. That is why our basic demand is to withdraw the 
settlers and end the presence of settlements in the areas from 
which Israel will withdraw. While this is being achieved, the 
Israelis must disarm the settlers completely. 
  ['Abd-al-'Aziz] This horrendous crime makes us pause to 
clarify things. How can the Palestinians be completely 
protected in the coming stage? 
  [Al-Husayni] The best temporary measure would be 
international protection. But the final formula must be total 
Israeli withdrawal from our occupied Palestinian territories. 
  ['Abd-al-'Aziz] Then you demand international protection? 
  [Al-Husayni] We demand international protection. But until 
this is guaranteed, several steps must be taken. They should 
start by disarming settlers, changing the army's orders to open 
fire, and, more importantly, take practical steps in 
negotiations by beginning to withdraw immediately from Gaza and 
Jericho. 
  ['Abd-al-'Aziz] What about continuing peace talks between 
you 
and the Israeli side? 
  [Al-Husayni] I believe that any talk of negotiations must be 
preceded with an agenda in which the settlement issue takes 
priority. 
  ['Abd-al-'Aziz] Do you mean that the issue of settlements 
should take a new form? 
  [Al-Husayni] It is no longer possible to defer the issue of 
settlements to the second phase; it must be discussed 
immediately. 
  ['Abd-al-'Aziz] What will the next Palestinian step be 
following this dreadful massacre against worshipers in the 
Ibrahimi Mosque? 
  [Al-Husayni] If Israel wants to maintain the peace process, 
it must take these measures. On the negotiating level, we must 
start discussing the issue of settlers and settlement and 
immediately start to discuss the final solution. Second, Israel 
must take practical measures, including disarming settlers and 
evacuating the settlers from the areas that might cause 
provocation. 
  ['Abd-al-'Aziz] Thank you very much, al-Husayni. 
  [Al-Husayni] My thanks to you. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

