<F P=100> Palestinian Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Sha'th Stresses Need for Palestinians' Protection </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  NC2702105594 Cairo MENA in Arabic 0949 GMT 27 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC2702105594 </F>
<F P=104>  Cairo MENA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Arabic </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Cairo, 27 Feb (MENA)--Dr. Nabil Sha'th, political 
adviser to Palestinian President Yasir 'Arafat, left Cairo for 
Tunis this morning. 
  In a predeparture statement, he said he will participate in 
the PLO Executive Committee meetings to discuss the 
repercussions of the al-Ibrahimi Mosque massacre, which he 
described as extremely serious. 
  We cannot imagine that the situation in the occupied 
territories will remain as it was before, he said. 
  Sha'th added: When we said that the real obstacle to peace 
is the settlements and the settlers, the Israelis insisted that 
Palestinian extremists, so they claim, are trying to abort the 
peace process. The massacre has shown who in fact is the 
aggressor and who is the victim. The settlement activity is a 
flagrant and continuing act of aggression; it is an illegitimate 
usurpation of the occupied territories and a Judaization of the 
land. 
  Sha'th stressed that the al-Ibrahimi Mosque massacre is a 
major blow to the peace process and an attempt to foil it. 
  We will discuss how to protect the Palestinian people in 
light of the international developments, and we will ask the 
world to ensure international protection for the Palestinian 
people through use of UN forces and observers, Sha'th said. 
  He said the PLO will ask the world to force Israel to disarm 
the settlers. 
  For the peace process to move ahead, Sha'th said, protection 
and security for the Palestinian people must be provided until 
the Palestinian forces take over full responsibility for the 
usurped land. 
  On transferring the negotiations to Washington, Sha'th said 
this is not a magical solution following the massacre. He 
added: The Cairo negotiations were not the reason for the 
massacre; on the contrary, the Egyptian leadership hosted and 
greatly supported the talks, and we were close to signing an 
agreement and starting the Israeli withdrawal. I believe that a 
transfer of the talks will waste some time. 
  Sha'th said that the United States must pressure Israel to 
achieve a just peace with the Palestinians. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

