<F P=100> Palestinian Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Sha'th: PLO To Discuss Protection Demands </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2702220694 Tunis Tunis-7 Television in Arabic 1900 GMT 27 
Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2702220694 </F>
<F P=104>  Tunis Tunis-7 Television </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Arabic </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpts] The PLO Executive Committee will hold a meeting 
in Tunis tonight in which the Palestinian delegations to the 
negotiations with Israel in Washington, Paris, Cairo, and Taba 
will participate. On the decisions and recommendations which 
are expected to result from tonight's meeting, Dr. Nabil Sha'th, 
political adviser to Yasir 'Arafat and the head of the 
Palestinian delegation in the Palestinian-Israeli negotiations 
on the implementation of self-rule in Gaza and Jericho, gave the 
following exclusive statement to this program: 
  [Begin recording] [Sha'th] This is the first major meeting 
to 
be held since the terrible massacre perpetrated by the murderous 
Israeli settlers in the Ibrahimi mosque in Hebron. The first 
responsibility of the PLO is to protect the Palestinian people. 
So we must discuss this subject in order to arrive at specific 
recommendations for providing protection for our people -- 
international protection and protection on the ground by the 
disarming of the settlers, the disarming of all the settlers, 
because without this protection cannot be provided for the 
Palestinian people. 
  In addition to this, we must also study the U.S. call for 
the 
negotiations to be held in Washington. We want to know what 
this call will add to the negotiations, how the change of venue 
will help to solve the problems facing the peace process, what 
role the United States will play in the coming negotiations, and 
at what level the negotiations will be. What are the main 
subjects -- will they include the protection of the Palestinian 
people or not? [Correspondent] [passage omitted] Dr. Sha'th, 
you have announced in statements to the press that future 
negotiations will focus basically on providing international 
protection for the Palestinian people so that what happened in 
Hebron will not recur. In your opinion what form should this 
international protection take? 
  [Sha'th] Many forms are known to the world. A few weeks ago 
a massacre occurred in Sarajevo in which the number of victims 
was similar to the number of Palestinian martyrs in the Ibrahimi 
mosque in Hebron. The result was a change in the international 
view of the Bosnian issue and of the protection required for the 
Bosnian people from the Serbs who were threatening the lives of 
the Bosnian Muslims daily. A minimum level of protection was 
provided which was not sufficient at all, but it was a minimum 
threat to the killers so that they would move their guns far 
from Sarajevo and protection would be provided for the Bosnian 
Muslims in Sarajevo. 
  There are international forces in Bosnia and in many other 
places -- Sinai, the Syrian-Israeli borders, the Lebanese 
borders, and others. The agreement we signed in Washington 
comprises suitable and agreed international protection. Until 
this moment Israel has been dragging its feet in discussing this 
item which provides for observers and international troops who 
will give the minimum protection, in addition to the Palestinian 
police who must replace the army of occupation when the latter 
withdraws. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

